We're nearly off the ice.

33:13.926 --> 33:14.591
(bleep)

33:16.962 --> 33:18.362
She's cracking.

33:20.699 --> 33:22.065
Holy (bleep).

33:24.737 --> 33:26.570
We're almost there.

33:26.572 --> 33:28.572
Come on, come on, come on.

33:28.574 --> 33:31.408
♪♪♪

33:31.410 --> 33:34.177
And artie is off the ice.

33:36.215 --> 33:40.517
I mastered the ice road that
I couldn't master before.

33:41.820 --> 33:43.787
There's a (bleep) rush to this.

33:43.789 --> 33:45.522
Some people skydive like
I ride my bike too fast.

33:45.524 --> 33:48.725
I do everything (bleep)
to the extent, right?

33:48.727 --> 33:50.560
To get that rush like.

33:50.562 --> 33:52.129
(chains clink)

33:52.131 --> 33:53.463
Now when that's cracking
and popping

33:53.465 --> 33:57.601
And all that stuff underneath
you this is kind of fun.

33:57.603 --> 34:01.471
I mean, I'm a little (bleep)
but I like this.

34:01.473 --> 34:03.573
Don't tell anybody
for (bleep) sake.

34:03.575 --> 34:06.476
Narrator: With the ghost of
the crossing behind him...

34:09.748 --> 34:10.914
(honking)

34:10.916 --> 34:14.251
- Well, we're here. We made it
all the way in here.

34:14.253 --> 34:16.653
Narrator: ...Art makes it
to remote sachigo lake

34:16.655 --> 34:20.223
And once again comes through
for polar.

34:22.461 --> 34:24.795
- We're startin' to unload
the truck.

34:24.797 --> 34:25.595
I conquered the last ice
crossing

34:25.597 --> 34:29.099
That I couldn't make last year.

34:30.069 --> 34:31.234
You know, if ya,

34:31.236 --> 34:33.670
If you fall you always gotta
get up and go again, eh.

34:33.672 --> 34:35.739
And I wanted another crack
at that lake.

34:35.741 --> 34:37.741
So you just gotta get up
and go again, man.

34:37.743 --> 34:38.508
Tackle it again.

34:38.510 --> 34:40.444
Thank you very, very much.

34:40.446 --> 34:43.280
Thank you again very,
very much.

34:43.282 --> 34:45.549
Thank you, buddy.
You have a good one.

34:47.453 --> 34:48.685
Might be a quick season, man,

34:48.687 --> 34:50.620
So I gotta get the hell out
of here as quick as I can.

34:50.622 --> 34:52.589
Get flipped back in here
perhaps with another load

34:52.591 --> 34:55.158
And it'll be great.

34:55.160 --> 34:57.294
(door shuts, shifts gears)

34:58.230 --> 35:00.564
(truck engine hums, honks)

35:04.169 --> 35:06.870
Okay, boys and girls we're off.

35:06.872 --> 35:09.573
Another one under my belt, eh.

35:09.575 --> 35:11.875
Now it's time to kick (bleep)
back,
man.

35:11.877 --> 35:14.144
Fasten your seatbelt, buddy,
cause we're empty,

35:14.146 --> 35:15.946
We're headed home.

35:15.948 --> 35:17.681
Hammer down.

35:21.453 --> 35:24.588
Narrator: While art breaths
a sigh of relief,

35:25.524 --> 35:27.791
800 miles to the northwest...

35:27.793 --> 35:28.558
In alberta...

35:31.997 --> 35:34.498
- You need to keep a good eye
on the oil pressure.

35:34.500 --> 35:37.134
Narrator: ...Lisa and darrell
are sweating it out

35:37.136 --> 35:40.303
On their company's longest
haul ever.

35:41.940 --> 35:44.074
- Check engine lights on.

35:44.076 --> 35:45.575
Staying on too.

35:45.577 --> 35:48.545
- You got an internal leak.

35:48.547 --> 35:51.448
Losing oil out of your
crankcase is not a good deal.

35:51.450 --> 35:54.251
We need to get these loads
delivered,

35:54.253 --> 35:56.686
Get that truck to the shop
and get it repaired.

35:57.923 --> 36:00.023
You do have oil in the water.

36:00.926 --> 36:01.858
Lots of it.

36:01.860 --> 36:03.527
Narrator: Midway through
the long journey

36:03.529 --> 36:07.230
Lisa's engine sprung a leak.

36:07.232 --> 36:09.132
Darrell: Which is what
we don't want.

36:10.068 --> 36:11.535
Narrator: Despite bleeding oil

36:11.537 --> 36:14.371
For 6 hours and 200 miles

36:14.373 --> 36:16.773
The engine hasn't seized up yet.

36:17.910 --> 36:20.310
- My engine's screwed.

36:21.713 --> 36:23.413
Hopefully, we're getting close.

36:23.415 --> 36:25.916
- Copy that.

36:26.418 --> 36:29.019
Narrator: Now it's a race
against the clock

36:29.021 --> 36:31.621
To see if lisa's truck can make
it through the final stretch

36:31.623 --> 36:34.591
Before the engine gives out.

36:34.593 --> 36:38.828
Lisa: Just question whether
we'll make it or not.

36:38.830 --> 36:40.263
(truck rattles)

36:42.801 --> 36:44.534
- This sucks.

36:44.536 --> 36:46.970
You know if this truck doesn't
make it out of here

36:46.972 --> 36:51.408
You know this business
could sink, could go down.

36:58.116 --> 36:59.549
Narrator: In the farthest
reaches of alberta...

37:03.855 --> 37:05.722
Lisa: Hope that I can
just make it.

37:06.625 --> 37:09.559
Narrator: The clock's ticking
on two renegade business owners.

37:12.397 --> 37:16.032
Darrell: Just a little father.

37:16.034 --> 37:18.401
Narrator: Pushing over
1000 miles

37:18.403 --> 37:22.973
The teams trying to pull off the
longest haul in company history

37:22.975 --> 37:24.507
If lisa's engine can hold on.

37:26.912 --> 37:29.446
- Hopefully we're getting close.

37:32.150 --> 37:32.649
(truck rattles)

37:35.621 --> 37:38.188
(truck engine hums)

37:44.596 --> 37:47.731
- I see a village off
to my right here.

37:47.733 --> 37:50.200
- You don't think that's
fort chip, do ya?

37:50.202 --> 37:52.135
- Yeah, off to my right.

37:52.137 --> 37:53.570
Narrator: Finally...

37:54.506 --> 37:57.574
The team reaches the outskirts
of fort chipewyan.

37:57.576 --> 38:00.443
- I cannot believe
that I made it.

38:03.282 --> 38:05.949
Narrator: Lisa limps into
the drop off point.

38:07.319 --> 38:10.420
- We survived the roads,
we got our loads delivered.

38:12.658 --> 38:14.124
Now that's how we do it.

38:14.126 --> 38:15.492
(on radio) you did good.

38:15.494 --> 38:17.227
Lisa: It was a long way.

38:17.229 --> 38:19.529
It was a tough trip
but we did it.

38:19.531 --> 38:22.999
Narrator: The truck can be
repaired in town for the ride
back.

38:23.001 --> 38:26.036
Lisa and darrell have
successfully expanded

38:26.038 --> 38:27.971
The winter roads map.

38:28.907 --> 38:31.541
Darrell: It's good, lisa, we
made our first load to alberta.

38:32.778 --> 38:34.444
It was huge progress for us

38:34.446 --> 38:36.946
As a company expanding
to a new province.

38:36.948 --> 38:39.316
We locked in the contract.

38:39.318 --> 38:42.085
This company's surviving,
this company's expanding.

38:43.255 --> 38:44.421
- Do you have somebody lined up?

38:44.423 --> 38:46.723
- I think so.
- All right, let's go get it.

38:48.794 --> 38:51.161
Narrator: While one convoy's
completed their mission,

38:51.430 --> 38:54.731
800 miles to the southeast...

39:01.740 --> 39:05.075
...The competitions still got
a convoy on the road.

39:07.579 --> 39:09.779
- Shamattawa's coming up
close here

39:09.781 --> 39:14.284
So we're gonna get in there,
find our trailers.

39:14.286 --> 39:16.186
Narrator: Under todd dewey's
mentorship.

39:16.188 --> 39:18.988
Rookie steph custance,
is only 50 miles

39:18.990 --> 39:21.391
From completing the road
into shamattawa

39:21.393 --> 39:25.061
On her first ice road's journey.

39:25.063 --> 39:27.263
- Hey todd, do you got a copy?

39:27.265 --> 39:29.199
- Yeah, steph, go ahead.
What's up?

39:29.201 --> 39:30.600
Steph: I'm just wondering uh,
are we going all the way?

39:30.602 --> 39:33.570
Are we gonna stop
or what's the plan here?

39:33.572 --> 39:34.938
- You know, we're this close,

39:34.940 --> 39:36.773
I think we should just get into
shamattawa

39:36.775 --> 39:39.709
Go find our trailers. You know,
our, our haul and uh,

39:39.711 --> 39:42.078
Gonna bunker down right next
to them for the night

39:42.080 --> 39:43.580
And that way we're just ready
to go for the first thing
in the morning.

39:43.582 --> 39:44.681
What do you think?

39:47.285 --> 39:48.351
- Sounds good to me, buddy.

39:48.353 --> 39:50.453
We pushed this far might
as well keep trucking.

39:50.455 --> 39:52.622
- Good attitude.
I like the attitude.

39:57.362 --> 39:59.295
She does a good job.

39:59.297 --> 40:01.364
She, she's got a lot of
enthusiasm and I like that.

40:01.366 --> 40:07.103
But we haven't got into
the hard stuff yet.

40:12.110 --> 40:14.177
- Hey todd?
Todd: (on radio) yeah,
go ahead, steph.

40:14.179 --> 40:15.445
- I'm coming up onto
the ice crossing here.

40:24.322 --> 40:25.722
So I got my first ice crossing
during the day

40:25.724 --> 40:30.226
And looks like I'm about to get
my first ice crossing at night.

40:30.228 --> 40:32.195
I'm feeling like the most
worked in first timer ever.

40:35.534 --> 40:38.301
(chains clink)

40:38.303 --> 40:40.370
Coming up to the ice crossing.

40:40.372 --> 40:46.142
♪♪♪

40:46.144 --> 40:47.811
- Now uh,

40:49.481 --> 40:51.815
That doesn't look right.

40:54.719 --> 40:56.386
Hey todd, do you got a copy
back there?

40:56.388 --> 40:58.321
- Yeah, steph, I'm right here.

40:58.323 --> 41:00.490
- I hate to be the bearer
of bad news but...

41:00.492 --> 41:05.028
I'm coming up to the shamattawa
night ice crossing right now.

41:05.030 --> 41:07.464
I'm seeing some barricades
up here, man.

41:09.134 --> 41:10.567
- What?

41:10.569 --> 41:12.035
Steph: Yeah, I don't know.

41:12.037 --> 41:13.470
I'm seeing uh, I'm seeing some
barricades.

41:13.472 --> 41:16.739
It doesn't really look like
I can get on to the ice.

41:16.741 --> 41:18.575
Todd: (on radio) oh, you gotta
be kidding me.

41:18.577 --> 41:22.512
Well, if there's barricades up
that only means one thing...

41:24.583 --> 41:27.750
That the ice crossing into
shamattawa is closed.

41:27.752 --> 41:30.053
That we are not getting
across the ice.

41:30.055 --> 41:30.620
- Oh, no way.

41:32.824 --> 41:36.192
Narrator: The convoy is stuck
dead in their tracks.

41:37.963 --> 41:40.763
Todd: They have barricaded it
as unsafe.

41:40.765 --> 41:43.032
We ain't makin' any money.

41:44.202 --> 41:47.303
Narrator: After 500
bone-crushing miles,

41:47.305 --> 41:50.673
Steph's first trip and the
convoy's critical mission

41:50.675 --> 41:52.709
Could be a complete bust.

41:57.215 --> 41:57.881
Narrator: Next time...

41:57.883 --> 41:59.582
Todd: (on radio) hold on.

41:59.584 --> 42:01.217
Narrator: On "ice road
truckers"...

42:01.219 --> 42:02.585
(chains clink)
todd: Whoa!

42:02.587 --> 42:06.022
Narrator: ...The warm weather
tears the roads...

